a, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mathilde","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."],"variants":[{"name":"Mechtild","meanings":["from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’."]},{"name":"Matilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]},{"name":"Mechtilde","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mathilde de Boubers de Bernâtre was born in 1148, in Boubers-sur-Canche, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France, her father, Jean de Boubers, was 32 and her mother, Louise de Benâtre de Gorenflos, was 20. She married Wallerand de Boufflers in 1163. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. She died in 1188, in Boufflers, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France, at the age of 40."},"et":{"1148–1188":"1148–1188","1144–1209":"1144–1209","1140–1188":"1140–1188","1164–1228":"1164–1228","1166–1231":"1166–1231","1168–1225":"1168–1225","1116–1179":"1116–1179","1128–1174":"1128–1174","1231":"1231","1164":"1164","1163":"1163","1174":"1174","1140":"1140","1228":"1228","1128":"1128","1116":"1116","1148":"1148","1225":"1225","1168":"1168","1179":"1179","1166":"1166","1188":"1188","1144":"1144","1209":"1209","Boubers-sur-Canche, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Boubers-sur-Canche, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Boufflers, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France":"Boufflers, Somme, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1148–1188":"1148–1188","1144–1209":"1144–1209","1140–1188":"1140–1188","1164–1228":"1164–1228","1166–1231":"1166–1231","1168–1225":"1168–1225","1116–1179":"1116–1179","1128–1174":"1128–1174","1231":"1231","1164":"1164","1163":"1163","1174":"1174","1140":"1140","1228":"1228","1128":"1128",